{"key":"post-14579028","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>14579028</id>\n<content>Flow hoods generate a lot of heat as a function of pressurizing the plenum, and to a lesser degree the heat from the motor itself.&amp;nbsp; You just have to turn the AC off and tough it out.&amp;nbsp; In my area, it rarely gets above 75F outdoors in summer, but even with cool temps, my lab heats up to 90F or more with the flowhood running.&amp;nbsp; AC units tend to collect a lot of mold due to the condensate, so I wouldn't run it near your lab area, ever.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Larger flowhoods are even worse about heating up a lab, which is the reason I'm still using my 12 X 24 flowhood, even though I'm running a commercial operation.&amp;nbsp; A larger flowhood doesn't speed up the operation much, but it sure as heck heats up the area more.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>14579068</next>\n<prev>14578891</prev>\n<first>14578617</first>\n<last>14585937</last>\n<when>1307549922</when>\n<utime>06/08/11 07:18 PM</utime>\n</post>"}